Only been there once for takeout sushi but here's my impression. I got the atomic roll and I'll second what someone else said, they make it with cooked (well done) tuna over the top which is not clearly spelled out on the menu. It's and interesting decision to say the least. I found it basically unappealing and left it on the plate. It's obvious sushi is not their forte. The roll was misshaped and small and not very tightly rolled. Tended to kind of come apart. The spicy tuna inside was sashimi but was that tuna mush that some places do. Not very appealing.  I was in there at an odd time, about 8pm on a Thursday, but there was literally nobody in there. The place is pretty dirty and grimy. I realize you probably don't want to pull the curtain back on most Asian kitchens but this one is open to the store so you'd think they would keep it a little cleaner, not so much. Also smelled like hot used frying oil in there.  To recap: They're other menu items may be great but I wouldn't really recommend the sushi and I'd like to see them do some deep cleaning.

Ok, so this wasn't my choice for dining in downtown Tampa, but I was meeting someone there so I gave it shot. We ordered 3 sushi rolls, the volcano, the Mexican and the atomic. There were two people in the entire  restaurant eating from their buffet menu which looked alright. It took them 35 minutes to make three rolls while we waited. The volcano roll actually tasted as if lava had solidified around some rotten fish. I definitely needed something cleanse my palate after eating this. Next up the "Mexican' roll tasted a little sweet, so unless they were referring to a churro, I am not so sure how 'Mexican' it actually was. Last but definitely not the least of their offerings, the Atomic roll came out and looked like it was topped off with some Bumblebee solid white tuna and some avocados that sat out a little too long. I flicked off most of the topping simply to avoid food poisoning and just ate the roll. These were ok at best but definitely better than the other two offerings. There are several sushi places to choose from downtown that are far and away better than Oriental Express. One can only surmise that the name for this establishment has a direct correlation to the amount of time that is takes for their food to pass through your body and not their service.

If you find me anywhere, please return me to myself. Hectic and chaotic does not do justice to my last couple of weeks. Thank goodness I had promised to not misbehave. I have not stopped. Aurora (my car) can testify that she has not rested. Indecisive me. Fickle me. Restless me. Today I went into four eateries. I was very hangry. The one who loves ribs wanted Chinese food today. He hinted and sighed and eventually just asked as I drove him to crew camp. Orient Express it was… Had Agatha Christie ever visited here, she might have not written her novel at all. Had she used me as one of the characters… I would have wanted to be murdered first. My nose is rather high maintenance. The food looked interesting (my mother uses this adjective when she does not want to criticize my accessory choices, the ones she really disagrees on.) Let me make clear that I don’t mind cafeteria style places. But I felt odor-slapped as soon as I walked in. I also feel very pressured when asked for my order immediately. Perhaps others feel catered to… or welcomed when that happens. Not me. So I was a tad nauseous over the smell (mind you, it was not a foul smell at all. It was the overwhelming combination of food choices mingling and marrying, overpowering and divorcing all at once.) Had I fallen in love with the bareness of the decorations… wait! What decorations? No, that did not help to distract me either. Have I mentioned how visually sensitive I can be? I love beautiful things. The Libra in me seeks beauty. Anywhere. Everywhere. I will refrain from reviewing the place in detail even when, until today (yes, no more), I called for deliveries and found the food okay. They serve abundantly. Huge plates to share… if you wanted to share okay food with family or guests. I have delivery-tried (which was like blind tasting until today): fried rice, white rice, egg rolls (quite oily tasting), bourbon chicken, orange chicken, egg drop soup, steamed dumplings, pepper steak and Lo Mein. Call and order with enough time so that your hangriness does not get the best of you. I went today. I felt catfished like in the MTV show. Our relationship platonic and beautiful. Maybe not the best, but okay. Nice… and nice is often good. Why did I try to ever meet?

when i called for delivery and a 9 year old, 10 tops!, picked up the phone i shoulda just hung up but i was too hungry to do so. long story short.. food was cold, didnt get what we asked for and boss lady didnt wanna hear nutin about no refund or re delivery..just excuse after excuse of why we were wrong and they were right. never again

Fast, hot and delicious lunch delivery. The food arrived about 1/2 an hour earlier than anticipated and the driver was super polite, even calling 5 mins out to let me know she was on her way.  I ordered the lunch special General Tso's (delicious) on fried rice (not enough egg, but good flavor), with crab rangoon (OMGAMAZING) and egg roll (meh). Will DEFINITELY order from them again!

Been ordering take out from these folks for years and years, I come from SF and am pretty picky sometimes.  This place...Great New York style chinese; always great portions and fast, and the family is super nice.  I like the terriyaki chicken, won ton soup is good, egg drop soup is always nuclear hot, and they deliver.  My girl likes the crab rangoons, make sure to remind them to bring the sweet and sour sauce with that.  Best in Downtown tampa/ChannelSide/Ybor area, for sure...
